SECTION 1.

The Juvenile and Domestic Relations Court.

Ã¯Â¿Â½There shall be created one Juvenile and Domestic Relations Court in the Province of Cebu for which a judge who shall possess the same qualifications, enjoy the same privileges and receive the same salary as judge of the Court of First Instance, shall be appointed by the President of the Philippines with the consent of the Commission on Appointments.

Provisions of the Judiciary Act to the contrary notwithstanding, the court shall have exclusive original jurisdiction to hear and decide the following cases in the Province of Cebu including the cities of Cebu, Lapu-Lapu, Toledo, Danao and Mandawe:

Criminal cases wherein the accused is under sixteen years of age at the time of the trial;

Cases involving custody, guardianship, adoption, paternity and acknowledgement;

Annulment of marriages, legal separation of spouses, and action for support;

Proceedings brought under the provisions of Article one hundred sixteen, two hundred twenty-five, two hundred fifty-two and three hundred thirty-two of the Civil Code;

Petitions for the declaration of absence and for the change of name;

Petitions for the declaration of absence and for the change of name;

Actions for the separation of property of spouses;

Proceedings affecting a dependent or neglected child, as hereinafter defined.

The court shall likewise have such incidental powers as are generally possessed by courts of first instance.

If any question involving any of the above matters should arise as an incident in any case pending in the ordinary courts, said incident shall be determined in the main case.
